### File Structure
```
ContentPublishingHub/
│
├── app.py
├── requirements.txt
├── README.md
│
├── data/
│   ├── users.txt
│   ├── articles.txt
│   ├── article_versions.txt
│   ├── approvals.txt
│   ├── workflow_stages.txt
│   ├── comments.txt
│   └── analytics.txt
│
├── templates/
│   ├── dashboard.html
│   ├── create_article.html
│   ├── edit_article.html
│   ├── version_history.html
│   ├── my_articles.html
│   ├── published_articles.html
│   ├── content_calendar.html
│   └── article_analytics.html
│
└── static/
    ├── css/
    │   └── styles.css
    ├── js/
    │   └── scripts.js
    └── img/
        └── (featured images and other assets)
```

### File Descriptions
```
app.py
- The main Flask application file containing all backend routes and logic.
- Handles routing for all pages: dashboard, article creation/editing, version history, article lists, calendar, and analytics.
- Implements reading and writing to the local text files in the 'data' directory.
- Manages user sessions/authentication (basic or placeholder).
- Implements version control, content scheduling, analytics aggregation, and collaborative features.

requirements.txt
- Lists Python dependencies, primarily Flask and any other needed libraries.

README.md
- Project overview, setup instructions, and usage notes.

data/
- Stores all persistent data in text files as specified.
- Each file corresponds to a data entity (users, articles, versions, approvals, workflow stages, comments, analytics).

templates/
- Contains all HTML templates for the web pages.
- Each template corresponds to a page defined in the specification, with the required element IDs for frontend interaction and testing.

static/
- Contains static assets such as CSS stylesheets, JavaScript files, and images.
- css/styles.css: Styling for the web application.
- js/scripts.js: Frontend JavaScript for UI interactions, form validations, and AJAX calls if needed.
- img/: Folder for featured images and other media assets referenced in articles.

This structure keeps the backend logic consolidated in a single file for simplicity, given the moderate complexity, while separating frontend templates and static assets for maintainability and clarity.

